t13.text: Compared to the bacteria that live and multiply in the rumen the number bacteria on the outside some grass or hay is minute. This it one of the ways that herbivores get B12. I know of no herbivore that gets it's B12 from eating soil.

t14.text: This is why a beef is so high in B12. They make huge amounts of it in their gut. Not from an injection.they may get once in their lives.

t15.text: Herbivores like deer, buffalo and cattle bacterially ferment the plant matter they eat in their rumen. Then digest the bacteria in their true stomach. B12 for ruminants is usually only a short term medication for when the rumen is not working properly.

t16.text: No animal gets a meaningful amount of their B12 from eating soil.

t18.text: The B12 is added to it, same with nutritional yeast. Yeast, in beer, bread or any yeast fermented food, does not make B12.
